<HEADLINE>
<P>
NEWSWIRE: AFTER 18 YEARS, RED SOX NO LONGER WANT EVANS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Dwight Evans, mainstay in right field at Fenway Park for almost all of his 18 
seasons, won't be back with the Boston Red Sox in 1991. 
</P>
<P>
Evans, one of the most popular Red Sox, has one of the most respected throwing 
arms in baseball. 
</P>
<P>
He learned Wednesday that Boston was not going to exercise an option on his 
contract at $1.3 million for next season. The buyout cost the Red Sox $200,000. 
</P>
<P>
Evans, who turns 39 on Nov. 3, has been plagued by a persistent lower back 
problem for about a year, and it limited him to a designated-hitter role this 
season. He batted .249 in 123 games with 13 home runs and 63 runs batted in as 
the Red Sox won the American League East title. 
</P>
<P>
Evans' 2,505 games with Boston were second only to Hall of Famer Carl 
Yastrzemski. He has 379 home runs and 1,346 runs batted in. 
</P>
</TEXT>
