<HEADLINE>
<P>
SAN GABRIEL VALLEY DIGEST: ARCADIA; 
</P>
<P>
SETTLEMENT IN SOIL REMOVAL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Redevelopment Agency accepted an out-of-court settlement totaling $1.3 
million from a national construction company for removal of contaminated soil 
at the firm's former branch. 
</P>
<P>
The city, which had sued Kiewit Pacific Co. for $10 million, has already 
received about two-thirds of the settlement amount. 
</P>
<P>
The agency bought the site at 301 E. Santa Clara St. in September, 1986, when 
Kiewit moved its offices to Santa Fe Springs. 
</P>
<P>
In March, 1989, about 50 barrels containing toxic residue were discovered on 
the site. This past March, a Superior Court judge fined Kiewit $50,000. Two 
months later, a federal judge ordered the firm to pay the agency for removal of 
contaminated soil. So far, the agency has received $850,000 in cleanup costs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
