<TEXT>
<P>
BLUFF CALLED: A bronze sculpture, titled "The Hide Drogher," on Wednesday 
became the crowning piece to Dana Point's new Blufftop Trail, honoring 
19th-Century traders in skins. . . . And what better way to salute the city's 
first large commercial venture than with another commercial venture? The statue 
was paid for -- along with the two-block-long walkway, a bridge and a viewing 
area on the blufftop -- by a Newport Beach developer. In exchange, the company 
gets to build on the site. Chris Woodyard and Len Hall 
