<HEADLINE>
<P>
SCIENCE; 
</P>
<P>
LAB PARTS WAY TO BALDNESS CURE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
LONDON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
British scientists today celebrated what they believe to be a breakthrough in 
the elusive quest for a cure for baldness -- test-tube hair. 
</P>
<P>
A team of scientists at Cambridge University announced that they had cleared a 
main obstacle to the development of an anti-baldness drug by growing human hair 
in a test-tube. 
</P>
<P>
"This is a real breakthrough," Terence Kealey, head of the research team, told 
a reporter. "No one has ever managed to grow hair in a laboratory before." 
</P>
<P>
The idea is not to grow a replacement head of hair in the laboratory but to 
allow effective testing of potential baldness cures on single human hairs. 
</P>
<P>
Kealey says the discovery makes the development of a cure for the age-old 
problem of hair loss just a matter of time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Brief; Wire 
</P>
