<HEADLINE>
<P>
PEOPLE'S PHARMACY: HAVE A BITTER PILL TO SWALLOW? NEW METHODS MAY PROVE SWEET 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOE GRAEDON and TERESA GRAEDON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Americans hate shots and love pills. Latin Americans believe that shots are 
real medicine and do not complain nearly as much as their northern neighbors. 
The French, on the other hand, are big on suppositories. 
</P>
<P>
Pharmaceutical wizards are moving way past such crude methods of drug delivery 
as tablets, shots, lotions, liquids and drops. High technology is entering the 
drugstore and is providing people with better ways of getting drugs where they 
belong. 
</P>
<P>
A whole generation grew up believing that when you swallowed a pill it went 
straight to the place it was needed, like a guided missile. Television 
commercials, like the one for a popular headache remedy, used a simplistic 
picture of a man with a hammer pounding in his head. The advertised solution 
sped right to the spot and stopped his hammer. 
</P>
<P>
Tablets, capsules, syrups and even suppositories must be absorbed from the 
digestive tract into the bloodstream. From there the active ingredients are 
spread from your nose to your toes through the bloodstream. All this can delay 
the benefits of the medicine. Additionally, the entire body is exposed to the 
chemicals, and side effects may result. 
</P>
<P>
Scientists are coming up with far more efficient systems and will be able to 
target drugs even more accurately than the television ad implied. 
</P>
<P>
Nicorette (nicotine resin) looks like chewing gum. It is actually a 
sophisticated drug delivery system that allows nicotine to be absorbed through 
the mucosal tissue in the mouth. 
</P>
<P>
There will soon be a nicotine patch that can be worn like an adhesive bandage. 
The nicotine will be absorbed through the skin directly into the bloodstream. 
Like Nicorette, this medication should help smokers who want to quit. 
</P>
<P>
Chemists are coming up with other ways to achieve long-lasting action. 
Norplant, inserted beneath the skin, releases contraceptive hormones for up to 
five years' protection from pregnancy. 
</P>
<P>
According to Dr. Robert Langer in Science magazine, tetracycline can combat 
periodontal disease at 1/1,000th the oral dose when it is inserted into the gum 
in a slow-release polymer form. 
</P>
<P>
Most exciting of all are the monoclonal antibodies produced by genetic 
engineering. When a drug is attached to one of these specialized antibodies, it 
truly does home in on the targeted cell. Researchers hope this approach will 
produce far greater success against septic shock, cancer and AIDS. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA102590-0254 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 297942 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
October 25, 1990, Thursday, P.M. Final 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Sports; Part P; Page 9; Column 4; Late Final Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
173 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
STRAWBERRY SAYS HE'D LOVE TO BE IN L.A. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
New York Mets outfielder Darryl Strawberry, who declared his free agency 
earlier this week, told a Los Angeles sportscaster that the Dodgers are No. 1 
on his shopping list for a new contract. 
</P>
<P>
"If the Dodgers are really, really, really interested in me, I'll be here," 
Strawberry said Tuesday in an interview with KABC. 
</P>
<P>
"That would be my No. 1 choice. I'm very determined to play here at home and if 
things can work out between myself and my agent and the Los Angeles Dodgers, I 
would love to be here at home and play. I mean, that's a dream that you always 
think about." 
</P>
<P>
Strawberry, a native of Los Angeles, is reportedly seeking a contract similar 
to the five-year, $23.5-million deal that Jose Canseco signed with the Oakland 
Athletics last summer. 
</P>
<P>
Until Nov. 5, the Mets are the only team permitted to talk money with 
Strawberry, who led New York with 37 home runs and 108 runs batted in last 
season. 
</P>
<P>
Fred Claire, vice president and general manager of the Dodgers, has said the 
Dodgers would be interested in Strawberry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
